## What can fail in this article's framing

A draft can accidentally present deferred syntax as current. A comparison can imply Beanstalk wins for every language and every domain. Later pages must keep **accepted syntax** and **current syntax** on separate labels when they diverge.

When you propose an example, ask whether the progress matrix already supports it. Teaching may still show accepted end-state architecture. It must say so.

## Why Beanstalk does it this way

**Alternative:** expose more general source mechanisms and move complexity into users and libraries.

**Choice:** constrain source mechanisms and keep semantic facts compiler-owned.

**Benefit:** fewer competing paths, clearer stage ownership, backends that consume facts instead of re-deriving meaning.

**Cost:** less metaprogramming flexibility and fewer familiar escape hatches.

## Roadmap and current status

- **Accepted design:** design-scope, compiler and memory authorities agree on the bias above.
- **Current implementation:** the progress matrix reports syntax and backend coverage without rewriting the bias.
- **Queued work:** config shape cleanup, canonical modules, numeric semantics and mixed backend plans remain labelled by plan status.
- **Deferred or outside scope:** rejected language families stay outside scope even when a neighbouring language loves them.

## Exit state

You leave with a design lens and a status vocabulary. Next: what the build command must decide before `#page.bst` even enters the compiler.
